WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:06.150 --> 00:00:08.000
Here comes the color!

00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:10.150 position:97%
Highest elevations in the Great Smoky Mountains are beginning to

00:00:10.150 --> 00:00:12.150
show great color.

00:00:12.150 --> 00:00:16.000 position:98%
Yellow buckeyes, sugar maples and birches are lighting up the treelines

00:00:16.000 --> 00:00:18.000
with their splendid displays.

00:00:19.000 --> 00:00:22.150 position:98%
Right now, a drive along Newfound Gap Road, Clingman's Dome Road,

00:00:22.150 --> 00:00:26.000 position:80%
or Blue Ridge Parkway reveals lovely rich foliage--

00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:28.150 position:70%
reds and yellows against a backdrop of green.

00:00:31.000 --> 00:00:34.000 position:95%
The peak of color above 4,000 feet is predicted to occur from

00:00:34.000 --> 00:00:37.000
October 12th thru the 21st.

00:00:37.000 --> 00:00:41.000 position:97%
Beautiful fall color means park roads will be busier than usual.

00:00:41.000 --> 00:00:45.150 position:92%
Areas like Deep Creek, Rich Mountain Road, Heintooga Ridge,

00:00:45.150 --> 00:00:50.000 position:98%
Balsam Mountain Road, Cataloochee, and Foothills Parkway can be great

00:00:50.000 --> 00:00:53.000 position:70%
places to see the color and avoid the crowds.

00:00:54.000 --> 00:00:57.150 position:95%
Or get out of the car and into the woods with an autumn hike.

00:00:57.150 --> 00:01:01.000 position:86%
You'll enjoy the Smokies comfortable fall temperatures.

00:01:02.000 --> 00:01:06.000 position:98%
And don't be surprised if leaves aren't the only color you see.

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:10.000 position:97%
Fall wildflowers like aster and goldenrod, are abundant still.

00:01:18.150 --> 00:01:22.000 position:97%
You can also see the curious heart-a-bustin' shrub near low to

00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:24.000
mid-elevation streams.

00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:28.000 position:92%
And it's hard to miss the red berries of flowering Dogwood,

00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:30.000
which is common in low elevations.

00:01:31.000 --> 00:01:34.000 position:88%
American mountain-ash, plentiful around Clingman's Dome,

00:01:34.000 --> 00:01:37.000 position:56%
also sports clusters of red berries.

00:01:37.000 --> 00:01:40.150 position:88%
These vibrant autumn fruits are a sign that fall is here

00:01:40.150 --> 00:01:44.000 position:78%
and the best fall color is just around the corner.

00:01:45.000 --> 00:01:48.000 position:84%
For more information about trees and their fall color,

00:01:48.000 --> 00:01:52.000 position:95%
check out <i>Trees of the Smokies</i>, available at the GSMA website

00:01:57.000 --> 00:01:59.150 position:67%
or at visitors centers throughout the park.

